    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin detour. Let's get straight to the science of the Maillard reaction. When you bake bread, the heat causes the amino acids and reducing sugars in the dough to react. This reaction begins at around 140 to 165 degrees Celsius (284 to 329 degrees Fahrenheit).\n\nHere's a simplified step-by-step of the process:\n\n1. The heat causes the reducing sugars (like glucose and fructose) to become more reactive.\n2. Amino acids, which are the building blocks of proteins, also become more reactive under heat.\n3. The reactive sugars and amino acids then undergo a series of complex chemical reactions, including condensation and rearrangement reactions.\n4. These reactions produce a variety of compounds, including new amino acids, sugars, and other molecules.\n5. The end result is a complex mixture of hundreds of different molecules, many of which contribute to the brown color and rich flavor of the crust.\n\nThe Maillard reaction is a form of non-enzymatic browning, meaning it doesn't require enzymes to occur. It's a key factor in the browning and flavor development of many cooked foods, not just bread.",
      "source": "target",
